### Mathematical statements

A [mathematical statement](/Mathematical_statement) is, at its core, a precise [proposition](/Proposition_(mathematics)) or an unequivocal assertion of some mathematical fact, a formal declaration, or a meticulously constructed mathematical entity. Such statements encompass a broad spectrum of declarations, ranging from the fundamental [axioms](/List_of_axioms)—the self-evident truths accepted without proof—to the profound [theorems](/List_of_theorems) that may be rigorously proved from these axioms. They also include [conjectures](/List_of_conjectures), which are intriguing propositions that remain unproven, or, in some cases, even unprovable, yet continue to inspire intense mathematical investigation. Furthermore, this category includes [algorithms](/List_of_algorithms), which are step-by-step procedures designed for computing the answers to questions that can be articulated with mathematical precision. These statements form the very language and content of mathematical discourse.

*   [List of algorithms](/List_of_algorithms): Step-by-step procedures for computation, the backbone of all digital operations.
*   [List of axioms](/List_of_axioms): Fundamental truths accepted without proof, the starting points of mathematical systems.
