### Mathematical objects

Among the countless entities that populate the abstract universe of [mathematics](/Mathematics) are a diverse array of "objects." These are not tangible items, of course, but rather rigorously defined conceptual constructs that serve as the subjects of mathematical study and manipulation. They include the fundamental [numbers](/List_of_numbers) that underpin all quantitative thought, the dynamic [functions](/List_of_mathematical_functions) that describe relationships and transformations, the foundational [sets](/Set_theory) that group elements, and an almost bewildering variety of entities referred to as "[spaces](/Space_(mathematics))" of one kind or another—each endowed with specific properties. This category also encompasses intricate [algebraic structures](/List_of_algebraic_structures) such as [rings](/Ring_(mathematics)), [groups](/Group_(mathematics)), or [fields](/Field_(mathematics)), each with its own set of axioms and behaviors. And, of course, there are countless other, often highly specialized, things that mathematicians invent and explore, pushing the boundaries of what can be formally defined and understood.

